    <div class="col-md-6">
        <h6>Topic B<br/>The Situation in Iraq</h6>
        <p>
            Since the U.S. intervention in 2003, passing through the official withdrawal of troops in 2011 and reaching the current situation, Iraq struggles to reconcile its various religious and ethnic groups in order to rebuild itself (Halliday, 2004; Visentini 2012; Knights, 2013). The Civil War in 2006 (officially ended in 2008) marked the climax of the sectarian crisis between Sunnis, Shiites and Kurds. It is well known that a divided and weak Iraq fits many foreign interests, as well as the complete elimination of the Baas and its political influence (Visentini 2012). This facilitates foreign capital entry in the country, as well as their immediate departure together with national wealth. In this fragmentation context, and in addition to the Civil War, the majority Shiite faction, led by Prime Minister Nuri al-Maliki, remains in power due to strong repression policies against the Sunnis (who historically had the political power) or due to agreements yielding political autonomy to the Kurds in the north (Khoury 2014; Lebel 2014; Johnson 2014).
        </p>
        <p>
            However, although it has been relatively successful in maintaining this situation for a few years, the Iraqi government sees itself increasingly unable to contain the now reinvigorated Sunni opposition due to the situation in Syria and its spillover in almost every way in Iraq - ideology, personal and material (Khoury 2014). In this context, a key actor for the future of Iraq are the sunni militants of ISIS (Islamic State of Iraq and Syria). ISIS is an affiliated al-Qaeda group, which represents the most destabilizing factor in the country today. The group policy mimics that of Al-Qaeda: hatred of foreign troops in the country, as well as the Shiites in power, in addition ISIS aims the creation of a Sunni caliphate encompassing Iraq and Syria (Meldensohn 2014).
        </p>
        <p>
            Accordingly, with fuel supplied by the Syrian crisis, ISIS has been growing impressively: the group has already taken whole cities (only last month were Ramadi and Falluja) (Meldensohn, 2014). In response, the repression has been tough, taken directly by the Iraqi Army and, together with the exclusion of Sunnis from the important positions in the government, can escalate quickly to another Civil War (Knights 2013; Lobe 2014).
        </p>
        <p>
            All this considered, it is of great importance that the UNSC looks carefully on the Situation in Iraq: how to isolate Iraq from the tension in Syria and avoid a new civil war, now enhanced by the Sunni supranational link? How the problem of sectarianism can be mitigated? Does a stabilized and strong Iraq interests to the major powers? These and other questions should be put on the table, since the topic is of high relevance for the international relations of Middle East and its future.
        </p>
